ated 1206":"omkring 1206","1232":"1232","1210":"1210","1270":"1270","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"nl":{"estimated 1206–":"circa 1206–Overleden","1210–Female":"1210–Overleden","1232–1270":"1232–1270","1206–Male":"1206–Overleden","1206":"1206","estimated 1206":"circa 1206","1232":"1232","1210":"1210","1270":"1270","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"en":{"estimated 1206–":"about 1206–Deceased","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1232–1270":"1232–1270","1206–Male":"1206–Deceased","1206":"1206","estimated 1206":"about 1206","1232":"1232","1210":"1210","1270":"1270","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Roos","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>De Roos</b>): topographic or habitational name referring to a house distinguished by the sign of a rose, or a metonymic occupational name for someone who grew roses, from <i>roos</i> ‘rose’.","Dutch: from the female personal name <i>Rosa</i> (from Latin <i>rosa</i> ‘rose’).","Dutch: nickname from <i>roos</i> ‘erysipelas’, an infection which causes reddening of the skin and scalp, applied presumably to someone with a ruddy complexion."],"variants":[{"name":"Roose","meanings":["Dutch: variant of   Roos   1–2.","German: variant of   Rose   and   Roos  .","English: variant of   Ross   1."]},{"name":"Roosen","meanings":["Dutch and Flemish: patronymic from   Roos   1–3."]},{"name":"Rose","meanings":["English, Scottish, French, Walloon, Danish, and German: from the name of the flower, Middle English, Old French, Middle High German <i>rose</i> (from Latin <i>rosa</i>), in various applications. In part, it is a topographic name for someone who lived at a place where wild roses grew, or a topographic or habitational name referring to a house bearing the sign of the rose. It is also found, especially in Europe, as a nickname for a man with a ‘rosy’ complexion (compare 4 below). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates and similar-sounding names from other languages, e.g. Hungarian <b>Rózsa</b> (see   Rozsa  ), Slovak <b>Róža</b> and Czech   Roza  . Compare 6 below and French   Larose   2.","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Rohese</i>, <i>Roese</i>, later <i>Rose</i>, <i>Royse</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Hrodohaidis</i>, <i>Rothaid</i>, composed of the elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>haid(is)</i> ‘kind, sort’).","English and Scottish: variant of   Ross  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Roos was born about 1206, in Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Lady Robert de Roos."},"et":{"estimated 1206–":"umbes 1206–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1232–1270":"1232–1270","1206–Male":"1206–Surnud","1206":"1206","estimated 1206":"umbes 1206","1232":"1232","1210":"1210","1270":"1270","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"estimated 1206–":"noin 1206–Kuollut","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","1232–1270":"1232–1270","1206–Male":"1206–Kuollut","1206":"1206","estimated 1206":"noin 1206","1232":"1232","1210":"1210","1270":"1270","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"estimated 1206–":"environ 1206–Décédé","1210–Female":"1210–Décédée","1232–1270":"1232–1270","1206–Male":"1206–Décédé","1206":"1206","estimated 1206":"environ 1206","1232":"1232","1210":"1210","1270":"1270","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Laxton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Laxton, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert de Roos est né environ 1206, à Laxton, Notti